<TITLE> Cabinet okays anti-graffiti, agro-study laws </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 13 (bdnews24.com)The cabinet provisionally approved two laws on Monday, one prohibiting graffiti and another to encourage agricultural research. "The Graffiti Writing and Poster Sticking Control Act 2009 has been approved in principle in the cabinet meeting," Abul Kalam Azad, the prime minister's press secretary, told a briefing after the cabinet meeting. "The law has been made to discourage people who love to stick posters and write whatever they like on anything." "Billboards, however, will be allowed to be put up for governmental campaigns and nation-building activities," Azad said. The cabinet also approved the Bangladesh Agriculture Research Council Act 2009. "This law has been approved to encourage researchers in the agriculture sector, to which the highest priority has to be attached." Azad said the prime minister directed all measures be taken to ensure that researchers remain free from financial concerns. The cabinet members and the prime minister's advisers attended the meeting
